An index longer than the rot is a sign of low risk of cancer
Men who have the index more than the rot are at risk of having a prostate cancer.
It is the surprising conclusion of a study published Wednesday by the British journal Cancer.
This may depend on the level of the male hormone testosterone.
"our findings show that the finger serves as a simple test of risk of prostate cancer, especially for men 60 years," proclaimed the co-author of the study Eeles Ros, a professor at the Institute for Research on Cancer at the University of Warwick.
The finger could thus help to determine which men should undergo testing for prostate cancer, especially in combination with the genetic risk or other factors aggrâvants as the antécedents family health, "said Eeles.
During the period of 1994-2009 it has followed with his colleagues in Britain more than 1500 patients with prostate cancer and at the same time nearly three thousand men.
More than half of the participants in the study had the index of the right hand is shorter than the rot.
For them and for the 19% of those who had the fingers of the same, we found the same probability of prostate cancer.
In the case of those who had the index more than the rot the risk, however, is down to 33 percent for men 60 years before the credit risk has reached 87 percent.
The report by length of two fingers - trained during the prenatal period - including different levels of sex hormones that the child in the womb.
Has less testosterone corresponds to an index.
Previous research had shown that it is precisely the testosterone, which assists in the development of a prostate cancer.
The pprofesseur Vacla Paces, Geneticist Czech actor and former president of the Academy of Sciences, said the KTC that he is aware of this study, but it seems that it is not, apparently, that the relationship between the length of his fingers and cancer is "fully demonstrated."
