The glacier Luciano Ferrari explains all the participants characteristics ideal ice perfect.
Is crucial not only good flavor, but also the flexibility soyeuse and the right consistency.
However, Luciano does not forget during training the icing on the cake of the superstructure national and, in general, the south: "The Italian ice is simply the best, and then it still retains a dose of romanticism."
The first step in the production seems quite simple.
Luciano pays basic ingredients, such as milk, cream, milk powder, sugar and stabilizers in a large mélangeur who said just 85 degrees through an electronic programme, then cools immediately to four degrees.
He then opened a spigot installed on the machine: it has a cream white basic pasteurized, the foundation of all types of ice milk.
The trainer was immediately deluged with question: Is it possible to make ice using only natural substances without stabilizing?
How can limit the personal pleasure of experimentation?
Mr Luciano warns against will be misled by the spirit of the time.
Anyone who does not speak of ice "made from natural ingredients," perhaps despite that used stabilizers: the more often a natural product, for example, of seed of guar achieved from the bean guar.
It is of course possible to make the ice without use of stabilizing, just to sell within 24 hours, otherwise it collapses and the customer croquera nothing other than pellet ice.
Some modifications of the base are permitted.
This becomes more exciting with flavourings.
The master Luciano establishes the difference between the ingredients that one acquires the fruit or sweets in the supermarket.
In addition, there are the powder and pulp.
"suppliers will try all of you pass dozens of ingredients are."
"however, you should simply try."
Or, in the words of sorbets fruit with sugar and fresh fruit.
Whether in the icy creams made from the dry whites, adding eggs becomes a cream and yellow is, when you add the cocoa powder, the basis of all the possible chocolate desserts.
Now, all participants in the past to use machines to ice.
Luciano invites them from time to time to produce four kinds of ice: vanilla, chocolate, moka and hazelnuts with or without eggs in the dry, with more or less of vanilla or other natural ingredients.
The different kinds of ice in the fruit are also subject to the same experience.
More aromatic substances, more fruit purée: from the point of view of taste, it is not necessarily better.
The ice to hazelnuts contains not necessarily the taste of the nuts, when it consists largely of hazelnuts.
The ice in kiwis, very popular, is made from the group using more fruit, less water and a little less stabilizing.
"only a balanced mixture is properly the taste of ice," says Luciano.
The manufacture of ice is an exercise in calculation: using the fishing with a lot of sugar, the quantity of sugar is reduced in the basic recipe.
An extra sugar is necessary for the ice lemon.
Luciano presents an apparatus with which it determines the sugar content of different types of fruit (wine producers use to measure the degree of Oechsle in the grape must).
Fortunately, the tables facilitate calculations.
The manufacture of ice does not require, as in the past, as much physical intervention.
This is not only the machine manufacturing autocategorizers mass basic aid.
There is also an apparatus which beats the mixture of ice available to make onctueux and reduced to low temperatures.
Despite all the automatisations, slight breakdowns are not excluded.
The Brazilian Gustavo is barbouille of fruit puree from head to feet and, thus, éclabousse his comrades studies when control of the colossal bowl mélangeur escapes.
The master Luciano is of the opinion that a "incident is likely to occur in every way: it is only a matter of time."
The supervisors in an ambiguous position
According to some sources, the industry that tested the cultivation of GM crops has infiltrated the European Food Safety Authority.
This accusation is now made by the group of experts Testbiotech which is regarded as an independent institute for the evaluation of the consequences of biotechnology.
"this sounds like a conspiracy theory, but we are well informed," said Wednesday in Munich Mr Christoph subsequent work, Director of Testbiotech.
There are reports that the president of the group of experts Efsa for genetically modified plants, Mr. Harry Kuiper and other experts Efsa are under contract with the pressure group Ilsi.
The latter is funded by groups such as Monsanto, Bayer or Nestlé.
Mr Kuiper has cooperated in the development of test requirements for the Efsa for GM crops and, as such, clearly in a situation of conflict of interest, according to the criticism by Mr subsequent work.
The requirements developed correspond verbatim, parts, the positions of the pressure group Ilsi and wear and the brand of the industry that would be controlled by the authorities based in Parma, Italy.
This is the second time that Testbiotech denounces a conflict of interest.
A high-ranking official of the Efsa has recently joined without condition or without transitional period the group relashionship Swiss Syngenta. in doing so, it has changed sides.
Not long ago, even the Radio Germany Central (Mitteldeutsche Rundfunk, MDR) had revealed the existence of personal relations between the authority of the European Union monitors and the industrial lobby, which has aroused suspicion of both the German Federal Environment Agency of the European Parliament.
However, the Efsa reluctantly accepted the existence of any conflict of interest.
An opinion indicates that it exploits all reliable data, including those of the industry as long as they are of good quality.
It does not prohibit experts working for the Efsa to establish contact with the sector.
But they should make them public.
Mr Kuiper admits that it works for the International Institute for life sciences (International Life Sciences Institute, Ilsi) based in the United States.
The organization sees itself as a neutral forum bringing together, among other things, in the field of science, industry and policy in order to assess the risks of biotechnology without being in the pay of a lobby.
In this case, the independent experts such as Mr subsequent work resent the fact that genetically modified crops are accepted without any trial of feeding the animals, and that it was not tested the impact of these plants on the environment.
"we want to know what are, for example, the impact of genetically modified maize in scope," says Mr subsequent work.
The current practice is to test only proteins isolated and not the whole plant, which makes it impossible to obtain reliable results.
"if we don't seek the risks, how can we find out?" ponders Mr subsequent work on an accusatory tone.
This is also the view of Mrs Angelika Hilbeck.
The scientist conducts research since 1994 in the field of genetics and is currently working at the polytechnic in Zurich.
In this region as the United States, and now also in Europe, the industry is trying increasingly to influence or discredit the scientific criticism.
That is why it is barely even researchers who are not linked to societies.
In the view of businesses, the critical studies would not be published.
Mrs Hilbeck says that "the industry control security research."
