Obama is cracking down on new drilling for oil
There will be no new drilling for oil in the Gulf of Mexico off the coast of Florida, the state's southeastern United States, over the years to come.
Washington has imposed a ban A ban equivalent and, thus, definitively abolished its original plans.
Even off the Atlantic coast, new drilling remain for the time being banned.
The Secretary of the Interior Ken Salazar made the announcement Wednesday.
This is the explosion in April, the platform drilling "Deepwater Horizon" which is at the root of this strict ban. it should remain in force at least for the next five years.
Faced with this accident which killed eleven employees and led to the greatest environmental disaster in the United States, President Barack Obama, under pressure from the opposition and industry, said he was willing to allow new drilling in the eastern part of the Gulf of Mexico.
Supporters of this solution want to reduce the dependence of the United States to foreign countries for supplies of oil.
The question of who bears the responsibility of the oil spill devastating in golf is not, to date, definitively resolved.
The British oil group, which is facing claims of billions, is at the centre of the accusations.
A commission of inquiry set up by Obama must present its conclusions in December.
In October, the Secretary of the Interior Ken Salazar had lifted the freeze drilling declared after the explosion of the platform.
Following this decision, various oil groups had immediately submitted requests for new drilling programs.
With control measures stricter and stricter safety, Obama and Salazar want to prevent another disaster.
The competent supervisory authority, which was discredited after numerous charges of corruption, is currently the subject of reforms in depth.
At the same time, Mr. Obama announced the lucrative tax breaks groups--to gas and oil.
The actors in this sector of activity now publicly that the flow of food in the Gulf would be significantly lower than is the case so far.
"the goal is to put a brake on the rapid growth of the oil and gas sector," according to the outcome of a current survey conducted in the sector by the auditing firm BDO, before the ban on drilling pronunciado Wednesday.
Indeed, the American Enery Alliance regrets the uncertainty of this sector: "Nobody knows exactly what will change with the regulation."
The investments made in new support projects have been postponed until further notice, at the expense of growth.
