The comparison is made.
The region where the Ogoni is a battlefield besieged for decades: More than 60 years ago, the first European explorers have entered here; the first was held in the 1980 s by Ken Saro-Wiwa. it was executed later. in 1993, the group Shell had to interrupt its production activities in this region because they had become very dangerous for its employees.
Even today, return Ogoni is prohibited in this society: As more than 2 million barrels of oil daily are being siphoned off by more than 5000 oil wells and 7000 miles of pipelines in the whole region of the Delta, three times as large as Switzerland, the country's oil fields are Ogoni untapped, because the situation is too unstable for the oil group.
Every few hundred metres stand in water tréteaux steel as outlandish sculptures: It refers very affectionate "Christmas trees" heads of drilling holes.
They have up to 50 years, most of which are consumed by corrosion until the benchmark.
Akpobari believes that a drilling of this nature is broken from time to time, as a steady stream of crude oil flows in the water.
According to expert estimates, more than two billion gallons spilled on the ecosystem in 50 years: Every year, the amount of oil equivalent to that which has passed into the sea at the time of the accident super-pétrolier "Exxon Valdez" 21 years ago off the coast of Alaska, one of the greatest environmental disaster in the history of humanity.
That must bear responsibility for environmental pollution persistent? the answer to this question divides the player.
For the group Shell, sabotage and the siphonage pipelines are responsible for more than 90 percent of the pollution. environmentalists, for their part, see the explosions of heads of drilling and oil pipelines perforated as the main causes.
In 2008, the American scientist Richard Steiner reproached the group Shell in Nigeria to enforce safety standards mostly lower than anywhere else in the world: Only the rate of defaults of pipeline-owners is "still much higher than alleures."
Some emerging forms of wetlands in a place that, from afar, like a workshop abandoned, full of work and installed in the open air: They are completely naked and covered in work.
A fire scintille under one of the many casks which sometimes associated with pipes, sometimes scattered without charge on the site must be répérés: a small refinery illegal.
It is warm crude oil in the water for several hours, explains Michael, the team leader.
At first, gasoline into a container through pipes, then, at the end of the African-Union-led drops kerosene fall and the end of diesel.
That is how Michael and his four colleagues produce daily four barrels of diesel and 300 litres: "That we reported 34 000 Naira," about $22.
The people of the Delta are taking advantage of the chronic shortage of fuel in the country's largest oil producer in sub-Saharan Africa.
Nigeria has only one refinery.
Refiners illegal can sell at a cheaper price than ridiculously low of just 40 euro cents per litre of diesel: Because they acquire charge their raw material.
It is offered by the "protectors" the network of oil pipelines leaking across the country of Ogoni. according to experts, the country loses in this way at least 16 million gallons of crude oil in the whole of the Niger Delta.
Only a small part insignificant to the raw material is temporarily stored illegally purifiée: The organised crime networks which are also among its members of politicians and military officials, instructing the lion's share of tankers and the dumping on the world market.
The militant Akpobari considers that the debate on the question of whether to attribute the environmental disaster, or rather the subversive activities at the population or production lax is purely academic.
"if the oil companies were not seen as intruders and if the livelihoods of the fishermen were not so deeply destroyed, there would be no sabotage or theft and illegal refineries."
But in the meantime, the relations of the Ogoni especially to Shell had so deteriorated that there was no question that the withdrawal of the group. "perhaps that operators with other nationalities, such as Chinese, will be better."
Then, Michael becomes nervous.
"it is high time that you déguerpissiez" the robust oil worker.
"the soldiers can appear at any time."
If the illegal refiners are surprised by special units of the armed forces, they will certainly not be the subject of an arrest, but at most they will offer bribes.
Even the soldiers mainly from the North intend to exploit as all Nigerians of the raw material.
"at any point of view, this rotten trick brought down our country well," Akpori regret.
