Mysterious work Caterpillar
The International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) has new indications on a nuclear program developed by Syria.
But refuses to take a position on this subject, let alone to be subject to the control of the agency.
On the night of 5 to 6 September 2007 to midnight, at least four Israeli F- 15 I fighter planes attacked a mysterious amorcé form design on Syrian territory.
It is situated on the shore of the euphrate; the largest city nearby is 30 kilometres is Dair as-Sur.
His name was included in the documents to the IAEA, because it is a question of the reactor that Syria has reportedly built with the help of North Korea in parallélépipède Stone, concealed in a valley marked by the absence of electrical current.
According to a briefing from the intelligence services of the United States, the CIA, dating from the end of April 2008, the current reactor, known as the nearby el-Kibar would be able to produce plutonium to manufacture nuclear weapons.
However, this technique is valid since the 1950 s.
The CIA has shown a video presentation containing satellite images.
Through the animation computer-aided, said the location of each component of the reactor before the destruction of the plant, which is a copy of the nord-Coréen miniature model of the nuclear plant in Yongbyon.
In addition, she has presented the photos showing the building, even within it.
It seems that the reactor was about to be put into service, but it was not yet equipped for fuel rods.
Today, more than three years after Israel's bombing, there is little more information than at the time, and even, with time the mystery deepens increasingly.
The former US president George W. Bush recently revealed in his memoirs that before the attack, the CIA was sure that Syria was building a reactor to el-Kibar, but of peu' indications that country was "an active nuclear weapons."
Some intelligence officers in Europe prefer to be more cautious about this and speak only of a "alleged reactor," even if they see the presentation of the CIA as "plausible."
Lack of hard evidence, and to the IAEA.
Asked about the way in which we have to ensure that there is a nuclear reactor, a diplomat from the United Nations has a laconic reply in summer by claiming that the IAEA had "documents enough to ask questions."
The Syrian certainly have abducted with haste the rubble of the "unused military building" and an orderly resolution of the ground.
However, in June 2008, a team of experts of the IAEA led by the former chief inspector Oli Heinonen, was discovered in el-Kibar traces of uranium produced by men.
In addition, the IAEA has received by a Member State images of satellite providers commercial showing the moment took the attaque. it seems that they are more eloquent than those presented by the CIA.
However, these photos are not available on the market because the sponsor anonymous, perhaps Israel, has exclusivity.
It is impossible for the IAEA to establish their authenticity in an objective way.
Syria has always ensured that she had never made a secret nuclear program and that it had not built reactor.
Damascus maintains that uranium found at the site comes from weapons used by Israel.
But the IAEA has rejected that argument after analysis of particles, describing it as implausible.
Since then, damas refuses any discussion on this issue, as on images of satellite.
In addition, Syria does not allow inspectors to conduct a second inspection on the site of el-Kibar and denied access to the rubble of the building destroyed by the bomb.
But, even Israel retains a stubborn silence.
Confirming the official position, Ehud Olmert, then Prime Minister's office at the time of the attack, recently said: "We will never comments on this subject."
That is how the investigation of this case for June 2008 without an outcome and that it "is increasingly becoming a serious problem of credibility of the Agency," as a senior Western diplomat in service at IAEA headquarters in Vienna, finally there is a serious violation of the treaty banning nuclear weapons.
The IAEA considers that progress, the existence of three other facilities must have "a functional relationship" with the alleged reactor.
So far, the inspectors have not indicated what facilities it is here, and what is their function or what they suspected to contain.
According to information published by the newspaper Süddeutsche Zeitung ," they are known within the IAEA respectively under the names of Marj as-Sultan, Masyaf and Iskandariayah also the name of nearby towns.
The Institute's independent Institute for Science and International Security (International Institute for Science and International Security) of Washington has identified these localities and discovered on satellite images of a complex near Masyaf that would most probably one of the objects suspects.
It is possible that he is in a military base or directly next to it; this is exactly why Syria refuses access of the three sites to inspectors from the IAEA.
In Vienna, that the Syrians fear that the group of inspection is in fact spies who would be sent on behalf of the United States by the IAEA to spy on military installations.
Indeed, it is an intelligence provided by the US secret agents who attracted the attention of nuclear inspectors.
The IAEA has information, including satellite photos, indicating that the vehicles were made by shuttles between the three sites and the parallélépipède stone to airlift substances.
A senior Western diplomat said in Vienna that at least one "facilities could be used for producing fuel."
He would have "no indications concerning sensitive activities," such as uranium enrichment and reprocessing; processes which are essential to the production of atomic weapons.
This type of reactor is certainly working through not enriched uranium.
Nevertheless, there is the stringency of plausible assumptions concerning fundamental questions: where should have come uranium and where she later separated plutonium needed to manufacture a bomb.
It is not clear whether the rubble, which could hide traces of great value, were stored in the three sites.
When the hundreds of trucks laden with land will disappear, nobody will have information on the storage of rubble.
For the IAEA, it is unlikely that Syria has been examined in 1998 the salt mine to al-Tibni, located just a few miles of el-Kibar, on the other side of the Euphrates, to see if we can agree on the storage of radioactive waste.
Afdeling recently the satellite pictures for the famous magazine Jane's, the former inspector of the IAEA, Mr Robert Kelley has established a link between them and the reactor in question.
The satellite pictures show that Syria has undertaken the work of Caterpillar in three suspected sites and moved huge containers when the IAEA began to demand access to these places.
Perhaps it is a coincidence, but it has not helped to allay the suspicions.
As he says in diplomatic circles that the IAEA has spent several months to develop a plan for the inspections to make. this plan was to allow Syria to preserve any military secrets. only time invested shows how much interest the inspectors in this case.
Meanwhile, Damascus has also responded to this proposal.
