The routine democratic
Support for democracy in Latin America continues to rise, as did to private enterprise.
The crime has become a greater concern than unemployment.
And Brazil is seen as more influential than the US in much of the region.
These are some of the conclusions of the last Latinobarómetro survey taken in 18 countries and published exclusively by The Economist.
Given that the survey was conducted on a regular basis since 1995, it follows the change of attitude in the region.
Two elements of the results of the survey, conducted in September and early October.
The first is the relatively sunny mood of Latin America.
The second is the growing stability in attitudes toward democracy and its institutions.
Support for democracy has increased significantly in several countries around the Pacific to South America (see chart 1).
For example, in Peru, where economic growth has averaged 6% per year since 2002, support for democracy from a minimum of 40% in 2005 to 61% this year.
It has also increased in Mexico, where the economy rebounded following a sharp decline in production last year.
But only about half of the respondents in Mexico and Brazil, the two largest countries in the region, are convinced democrats, depressing the regional average (see chart 2).
Some 44% of respondents from the region were satisfied with the way democracy in their countries worked in practice; it is the same figure as last year but with a sharp increase on the 25% in 2001 (Chart 3)
Some 34% said they had confidence in the parliament of their country and 45% in their government, the same as last year; but rising sharply compared to 2003 (17% and 24% respectively).
Ten years ago, the economic problems in Latin America have undermined support for democracy.
If that has lasted for the global financial crisis, this is certainly due to the fact that many of America was a brief recession and have benefited from a strong recovery.
In addition, a network of social security has helped to protect the poor.
(the United Nations Economic Commission for Latin America reported this week that the proportion of Americans living in poverty have risen only slightly in 2009 and has fallen again this year, to 32%.)
But the mood varies considerably from one country to another (see chart 4).
The good economic performance of Brazil and the popularity of the incumbent president, Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva, is a widely shared sense of progress
What is more rare in Mexico and Central America, where the recession has been more severe and where violent crimes have worsened.
This is only the second time since the survey began that more respondents across Latin America as a whole have cited crime rather than unemployment as the most important issue for their countries (see chart 5).
Approximately 31% say that they or their had been a victim of a crime in the past year; however, this figure is down from 38% last year and is the lowest since 1995.
A more robust economic performance is reflected in the rise of support to private enterprise and the market economy: approximately 71% of respondents from the region say that private enterprise is essential for the development, against 56% in 2007 (see chart 6).
Some 58% of the market economy is the only system that will make their developed country, against 47% last year.
Interestingly, 62% of respondents in Venezuela are of this opinion (and 80% support private enterprise); even if their left-wing president, Hugo Chavez, expropriating many private companies.
Brazil is the biggest player in the region, mentioned by 19% (compared to 18% last year), followed by the US (9%, unchanged from last year) and Venezuela (9%, down by 11% since last year)
But the United States are considered the most influential country by respondents in Mexico and throughout much of Central America, while Venezuela enjoys this distinction in Ecuador, the Dominican Republic and Nicaragua.
A vote tainted
No one expected to have a general election perfect in Haiti on November 28.
But it was far worse than the "outsiders" who wanted to help the countries affected and plunged in fear.
It was presented boxes and a new election, ballots in the goutières, polling stations ransacked and intimidation
Polling stations opened late in the evening.
Many of Hatïens, including many who were displaced following the earthquake in January, had slipped in the neighbourhood finding out where to vote.
Some of them were eventually abandoned.
A dozen presidential candidates, including several favorites, denounced alleged fraud and have called for the annulment of the election.
Protests, sometimes violent, have exploded across the country.
Nevertheless, Edmond Mulet, the top official in Haiti to the United Nations, sees the event as "an election fairly good in many respects."
Observers from the Organization of American States and the Caribbean Community said cautiously that "they do not believe that these irregularities, as serious as they are, necessarily had overturned the process."
In other words, the show continues.
The electoral authority, whose opponents are beholden to outgoing President René Préval, unpopular, and its candidate, Jude Célestin, must announce preliminary results on 7 December.
The expected second round is scheduled for January.
Any hope in the election is not lost.
The two opposition candidates, Michel Martelly, a musician of rap, and Mirlande Manigat, a former first lady, withdrew from their initial appeal that the vote be declared invalid.
But there may be problems if Mr Célestin, who has little or no support common among voters, is declared by the electoral authority as having reached the second toura reached the second round.
With a cholera epidemic raging, and more than 1 million earthquake survivors who are still living in tents, it was feared that participation would be.
Myself, many Haitïens wanted to vote but were prevented from doing so because of the disruption.
Nearly 250 000 identity cards, needed to vote, were not yet distributed shortly before the election.
The stakes are high.
Donors see the election of a legitimate government and as an important step in the reconstruction of Haiti.
And so, it is clear, the Haitians are themselves.
The toes to the center
The weeks after having become suddenly widow, Cristina Fernández, president of Argentina, has benefited from a wave of public sympathy that has improved his approval rating of 20 points, more than 50%; it is to its highest level since it was elected in 2007.
However, transforming it into a successful campaign for a second term in an election next year might depend on the choice of Mrs Fernández, visibly in mourning, that it would abandon the intransigence of his late predecessor and husband, former political partner, Néstor Kirchner.
And, in this connection, the signs remain unclear.
Mr Kirchner, who has continued to manage economic policy, even after his wife takes as chairman, used to develop budgets which under-appreciate tax revenues, economic growth and inflation.
This has allowed the first couple to spend the extra money at will.
The government of Mrs Fernández has lost its majority in Congress last year, on paper.
But the opposition is divided, and the situation was thrown into disarray following the death of Mr Kirchner a heart attack on 27 October.
Some dissident members of the ruling Peronist movement have rallied to Ms Fernández.
But following chaotic (where a parliamentary hit in the face with one of his peers and others have accused the government of corruption), Congress did not approve the 2011 budget.
"I am not going to fight," said the president.
Currently, the 2010 budget will be implemented next year, leaving the president still more flexibility to spend at will.
The economy overheating widely: it is likely to grow by nearly 9% this year.
The official rate of inflation is now at 11.1% but many estimates private and wage claims of unions, see this figure close to 30%.
Mr Kirchner, who took office in 2003 when Argentina feared an economic collapse, has made a priority of growth and poverty reduction, rather than the control of inflation.
He has refused to deal with the IMF, it has harassed the private sector and purged the INDEC, the statistical office, which conducted the forgery of official statistics on inflation.
Ms Fernández can now moderate these policies?
She has called for talks between private companies and union leaders.
And officials say they want to limit wage increases next year to 18%.
The economy has been driven by high world prices for agricultural exports to Argentina.
But inflation has eroded the boost to growth following a sharp devaluation in 2002.
This is perhaps why Mrs Fernández shows signs of wanting to re-establish the financial relations of Argentina to the rest of the world.
This year, the government has concluded an agreement with bondholders who had rejected a previous restructuring of debt on which Argentina had not settled its deadlines in 2001.
Now Ms Fernández seems to be edging towards year agreement with creditor governments grouped in the Paris Club, to which it owes some $6,7 trillion.
The Kirchners have always insisted that this could involve a surveillance by the IMF, as is customary.
But last month, Boudou Amado, the Minister of the Economy, announced that the fund would provide "technical assistance" to design a new national consumer price index, which looks like a prelude to the clean-up of the INDEC.
It is not clear if Ms Fernández wants to remain in politics beyond the end of his mandate, now that her husband is no longer at his side.
If it does, it needs to win the support of the middle class, among which the kirchnerisme is very advocated.
When Argentines will be returned to their summer holidays in Mars, the wave of sympathy for it has fallen.
If it wants to win another election, it will decide whether to repudiate or not, without noise, many of the policies of her husband.
A demi-hourra for China
The Taiwanese voters are in a kind of closer links with the mainland.
What Taiwan think of its big brother on the other side of the Strait?
More than 7.5 million voters are presented on 27 November, 70% of those eligible to elect mayors and municipal councillors in five urban districts, in what is seen as a general assessment of the president, Ma Ying-jeou.
Mr. Ma has almost become a substitute for the feelings of the continent, with ties to innovative business, including a free trade pact, in the largest reorganization of relations with China itself since 1949.
Mr. Ma passed the test, but only just.
Although his party Kuomintang (KMT) has won three of the five halls, it has failed to win a majority of the votes.
Instead, the démocrate-progressiste Party (DPP), which has opted for the independence of Taiwan, has won nearly 50% of all the votes for the KMT's 45%.
If it had been a presidential elections, Mr Ma would be in trouble.
Since he was elected two years ago, the share of the vote for his party has fallen by about 8%.
For the first time, the DPP has attracted voters, even with the KMT in municipal councils.
The event has revealed most of the main topics of Taiwanese elections, including trucks and aggressive campaign flags of gathering mass with girls danced with minimal.
An assassination attempt mysterious mandatory has also been perpetrated.
Sean Lien, son of Lien Chan, honorary president of the KMT, has done an as-and-when-needed election to a candidate from the KMT on the eve of the election.
A man of the crowd in the young Mr. Lien, purely across his face, wounding and killing a bystander.
Strangely, it has not been determined if the shooter wanted to hurt Mr. Lien or settle a dispute with the candidate.
Anyway, said Tsai Ing-wen, the leader of the PDP, the murder has had an impact on the election as leader of suspicion over the DPP and turned voters toward the KMT.
Perhaps the biggest winner of the elections was China.
It was striking that the question of the continent itself was absent.
Instead, the candidates have been with plans for public housing and job creation.
Taiwan enjoys usually its de facto independence and dislikes the military threat from China.
Thus, the KMT tends to avoid putting its links with the government in Beijing.
But this time, the DPP also has failed to stir up anti-China sentiment.
This is the answer to a new awareness that Chinese companies are essential to the economic survival of Taiwan.
Mr Ma, for its part, has demanded a confirmation on whether its policy on China was acceptable to the majority of Taiwanese.
It is expected that the government in Beijing continues to provide commercial facilities, in line with its strategy to lure Taiwan, of the eerie.
China lost no time to send a negotiator in Taipei to organize a summit on the protection of investments and medical cooperation.
Of course, she would also like to see a political integration; but let's go back to basics.
Better to wait until after the presidential election of 2012.
The DPP has reinvented itself anyway.
Two years ago, it was bad: its former leader, Chen Shui-bian, had been sent to prison on charges of corruption.
President from 2000 to 2008, it was a provocative in favour of independence.
But a new generation of moderate has grown under the leadership of Mrs Tsai and the PDP is working hard to attract professionals and young people.
Mrs Tsai has been hailed as a DPP candidate for the presidency, as Tseng-chang Su, who has served under Mr Chen.
Their party is doing its best to show that he, too, can engage with Beijing.
Mrs Tsai announced plans for a panel of experts to act as a point of contact between the DPP and China, on condition that their talks can take place without preconditions.
Mrs Tsai tells the Taiwanese public that his party is an alternative "trustworthy" compared with the shotgun approach to Mr. Ma on China.
Mr Chen seems exasperated by this change.
In a statement issued from his cell, he said that candidates of the PDP would have fared better if they had insisted on the fact that Taiwan is a separate country.
He has even ordered Mr Su, a pragmatic, not to run for president.
Even without the intervention of Mr Chen, the DPP will find it hard to choose between its potential candidates.
It is that the KMT makes introspection.
The assessments of Mr. Ma were weak, despite economic growth, the KMT candidate did not want to campaign with him.
His unpopularity seems to be largely due to unemployment and a widening gap between rich and poor.
A spokesman for the KMT said that his cabinet and local offices will be revised.
The good results of the PDP suggests that the support of Taiwan for the rapprochement.
At the same time, most of the Taiwanese see economic integration with China as inevitable.
According to Antonio Chiang, a prominent columnist, "the point of no return is already past."
