A microbe tolerant arsenic raises the possibility of new types of life on Earth, or elsewhere.
The discovery of a strange bacteria, which can use arsenic as one of its nutrients, broadens the scope to find new forms of life on Earth and perhaps beyond.
Although researchers have discovered the bacteria unusual here on Earth, they say it shows that life opportunities beyond the major elements which were considered essential.
"this body has a dual capacity."
"it can be developed with phosphorus, arsenic."
"that is why it is very special, even though it is far from being a form of life really" foreign, "said Paul C. W. Davies of the University of Arizona State, co-author of the report in the online edition of the journal Science on Thursday.
Six major elements have long been considered essential for life: the carbon, hydrogen, oxygen, nitrogen, phosphorus and sulphur.
But the researchers found that the bacteria, discovery in the lake Mono, California, is able to continue to grow after having replaced phosphorus by arsenic.
"one wonders what is still possible," said Ariel Anbar D. of the University of Arizona State, co-author of the report.
The discovery is important in the search for life beyond the Earth because researchers must be able to recognize life, to know what life is like, said Anbar.
The study focuses on a microbe found on Earth.
However, the announcement of a press conference to discuss, who did not divulge the details of the discovery, has generated widespread speculation on the Internet that the report could disclose the discovery of extraterrestrial life.
This has not been the case.
The discovery "shows that, in other environments, organizations may be able to use other elements to power biochemistry and that the" standard "elements, which we consider to be absolutely necessary for life, could not be fixed," said Charles Cockell, a professor at the Institute of Science and spacial, Open University in Milton Keynes, UK.
Cockell was not part of the research team.
"this work is new because it shows the substitution of one element to another basic biochemistry and biochemical structure," said Cockell.
This was not an accidental discovery.
Felisa Wolfe-Simon of the Institute of Astrologie NASA, who led the study, has chosen the lake Mono because it has high levels of arsenic.
Arsenic and phosphorus are chemically similar; thus, she speculated that a microbe exposed to two substances might be able to replace one another.
"arsenic is a toxic mainly because its chemical behaviour is very similar to the phosphorus."
"as a result, find it hard to distinguish these components separately."
"but arsenic is sufficiently different to that it doesn't work exactly as phosphorus; he got inside and, somehow, removing the work of our biochemical machine," said Anbar.
Researchers have collected the bacteria known as GFAJ- 1 and exposed to increased concentrations of arsenic that she was able to adapt and grow.
The microbe grows better with phosphorus but the fact that he can live with arsenic instead raises the possibility that a form of life using arsenic can occur naturally, or elsewhere on Earth or on another planet or moon where arsenic is most common.
Jamie S. Foster, an assistant professor of microbiology at the University of Florida, said that the idea that the arsenic could be replaced by phosphorus, was not new, but nothing has ever shown that it could work.
Arsenic is more frequent early in the history of the Earth, she says, so researchers have speculated that the first life forms could use it.
This suggests there may be other ways to form life, not just how life on Earth was formed at the beginning, "said Foster, who was not part of the research team Wolfe-Simon.
The research was funded by NASA, the Department of Energy and the National Institute of Health.
