The lion is ready to be new, the restructuring of GMMs is awaiting the final green light to the court
After 18 months of turmoil and uncertainty, GMMs has finally been given the green light to start from scratch.
A federal bankruptcy judge in New York, has officially on Thursday praised the plan "pre-packaged" by the creditors that about $5 billion of debt would be erased, paving the way for the company, with 86 years of existence, to concentrate its efforts on the production and distribution of films and television.
With Thursday's decision, that the plan meets the requirements of the code of the bankruptcy of the United States, no legal obstacle will remain to GMMs to stay afloat under the tutelage of the founders of entertainment Spyglass, Gary Barber and Roger Birnbaum, who will become the Directors-General of what will be a lighter.
The staff will be reduced to about 320 to 400 in the first place.
GMMs will not emerge really Chapter 11 as; Chase concludes a credit facility of $500 million, planned to finance new operations and products of GMMs.
She is currently distributed under licence by the investment bank, which has itself to $75 million, and should be funded to mid-December.
The process of restructuring of the studio began in May 2009 when the investment bank Moelis & Co. was committed to advise the direction on how to get its finances since it did not have the resources to pay the interest amounting to $300 million per year.
In August, the general manager, Harry Sloan, was replaced by Stephen Cooper, a former CEO of Enron and an expert in recovery, known for his work in Krispy Kreme Doughnuts.
Attempts to Moelis and Cooper to resolve the financial difficulties of conducting research and satisfy the more than 140 creditors of the studio took much longer than expected.
After several months of discussions, the parties have agreed, at the end of 2009, to put the company up for sale.
However, the auction attracted few bidders including none of them was willing to pay the sum of $2 billion to creditors were to research.
In the spring of this year, we have to redo while the team of GMMs had started work on a restructuring plan which, after months of disagreements and internal debates, was finally approved by the creditors at the end of October.
When officially GMMs fate of bankruptcy in the following weeks, companies Moelis and Cooper bonuses for their work.
Moelis & Co., which has already received $1.2 million, will receive a payment of $9.5 million.
Companies of Cooper, who collected $375 000 per month for their services company, will receive a "bonus" of $4 million.
Barber and Birnbaum account to boost production of GMMs, who has only one film this year, and set up an annual list of seven or eight films come from 2012.
They also intend to co-finance two films based on "the Hobbit," with Warner Bros
The studio must conclude a separate loan between $265 000 and $275 million in 000 to fund its share in these two films, which must be done by Peter Jackson.
The investor Carl Icahn, which holds about 18% of the debt of GMMs, has tried to achieve a merger of the studio with Lions Gate entertainment, where it is the largest shareholder.
However, the recent discussions between the two companies have not reached an agreement.
