Prosecutors did not inculperont Senator Ensign
Prosecutors of the Department of Justice have lifted the criminal charges brought on Senator John Ensign, resulting in a case linked to an assistant of a former campaign and his efforts to obtain a work of lobbying for the husband of the woman, have anoncé Wednesday lawyers Senator.
The decision ends the legal threat most serious faced by Mr Ensign, Republican of Nevada who was seen as a possible Republican candidate in the presidential election of 2012 until the scandal surrounding his case to make headlines national last year and hurt his career.
The office of Mr Ensign said he was "very pleased" by the decision, which is the result of a year-long investigation.
The senator could still be exposed to disciplinary measures taken by the Senate Committee on Ethics.
Lawyers for Mr Ensign said the Department of Justice had "informed that Senator Ensign was no longer subject to the investigation and that it does not intend to maintain any charges against him in this matter."
The Department of Justice has refrained from comment on this subject.
The announcement came as something of a surprise to many lawyers ethics outside the Department of Justice, under which there would be significant evidence indicating that Mr. Ensign would have conspired to violate a criminal prohibition federal lobbying.
Interviews, e-mails and other documents, first reported in October 2009 in The New York Times reported that Mr. Ensign had helped Douglas Hampton, who was one of his assistants, to obtain a work of lobbying to win the silence of Mr. Hampton and his wife, Cynthia, relating to the case of Senator with it.
Mrs Hampton once served as treasurer during a campaign Ensign.
Mr Ensign has approached a number of cape.uwaterloo.ca policies to find work for Mr. Hampton and, secondly, he defended their rights after they have hired Mr. Hampton lobbying for them, according to documents and interviews.
Given that Mr. Hampton had recently been a collaborator of Mr. Ensign, he was banned for a year by the law of lobbying from his former employer or the Senate as a whole.
Ethics experts have argued that the unusual agreement between Mr Ensign and Mr. Hampton, who were close friends before the affair, seems at odds with the absolute ban of the revolving door of lobbying.
According to the evidence that has been made public, "there seems to be a prima facie case of a conspiracy to violate and violation of the law of the revolving door," said Stanley Brand, a lawyer in Washington who specializes in defending clients of an investigation by the government.
Although the judge's department has refused to explain the reasoning behind the decision in the case Ensign, Mr. Brand and other lawyers in ethics have said that the department seemed to be wary of political prosecutions after a number of setbacks cashed in by his section of the public integrity, including the decision last year to abandon the prosecution against the former senator Ted Stevens accused of lack of prosecution.
The federal prosecutors have clearly afraid to take up arms, "said Melanie Sloan, executive director of Citizens for Responsibility and Ethics in Washington, a group that has received several complaints against Mr. Ensign in the case.
"this basically says high-ranking government officials can now assumes the laws don't apply to them," she added.
Paul Coggins lawyer, principal of Mr Ensign, said in an interview that he had received on Monday a phone call from a prosecutor of the Department of Justice and the next day, saying that the department did not seek charges against his client.
The team of lawyers to Mr Ensign had cooperated with prosecutors to try to persuade them that the senator, as his office has reaffirmed Wednesday in a statement, "had acted in accordance with the law."
Mr Coggins refused to specify the legal arguments that he had done.
"I am not comfortable going into the details of my discussions with the Department of Justice, except to say that we believe they have made the right decision," at-il said.
Last month, the Federal Elections Commission has decided to abandon an investigation following a complaint by the independent ethics group, claiming that the payment of $96,000 by the parents of Mr Ensign to Hampton violate federal election law.
The electoral commission has said that it was not enough evidence to prove that the money was anything but a gift.
NV Energy, a major Nevada who has long supported Senator, is a company for which Mr Ensign has helped Mr. Hampton find work of lobbying.
An e-mail sent in December 2008 showed that, after the company has welcomed Mr Hampton as a lobbyist, the chief of staff, John Lopez, Mr Ensign has contacted Mr. Hampton and told him that he "martelait" the Ministry of the Interior on an issue.
Mr Ensign also attended a lunch with Mr. Hampton and another client of Nevada, Allegiant Air, and he asked the secretary of transportation to arrange a meeting on behalf of the airline after hiring Mr. Hampton to lobbying.
When the news of the case have surfaced last year, Mr Ensign apologized to his constituents and resigned from his position as leader fourth Republican in the Senate.
After having maintained a low profile for several months, Mr. Ensign said two weeks ago that he intends to run for a third term in the Senate.
In announcing that Mr Ensign was no longer the target of a criminal investigation, his spokesman, Jennifer Cooper, said he hoped that the ethics committee quickly follow the example of the Department of Justice and bring an end to its investigation.
Senator Ensign looks forward to his hard work on behalf of the people of Nevada, "she says.
The appeal of Cheshire vice-chairmanships to Twitter
A dozen of them were in the process of getting ahead in the rows of the courtroom.
They were all minutes reports of horrific testimonies via Twitter.
In the end, the defense said that there were more than 140 000 messages on trial in the case of rape and children attached to their bed in a house that was set on fire.
On Thursday, the trial widely followed by Steven J. Hayes, who was convicted of the murder of three members of the family, Cheshire in Connecticut, should lead to a formal end where the judge would impose the death penalty, adopted by the board.
But lawyers for Mr. Hayes were present in court against the arguments of appeal, likely to take the courts for years.
What is of course, is that the intense reporting on the trial - and the widespread use and extended by journalists on Twitter - have created a "atmosphere of circus," a saturation if widespread and instantaneous with incendiary details that the board has been influenced by the passions of the public.
The request could push the judges to call for a debate on the question of whether the new technologies require new rules in the courtroom.
"I experienced at this trial; I think there is a real danger, the introduction of new technologies in the courtroom violates the rights to a fair trial," said Thomas J. Ullmann, lawyer for Mr. Hayes, chief lawyer.
The trial judge, Jon C. Blue Superior Court of State, was laconic rejected claims in the judgment last week, saying that the media were "carefully controlled" and that there was no evidence that the jury would have been driven by passion.
But this does not seem to be the last word on the issue.
The appeal courts recognize for decades that the media coverage of the notorious cases may raise questions about the fairness of a trial.
In a judgment of 1966 landmark, the United States Supreme Court has overturned the conviction of an osteopaths Cleveland, Dr. Sam Sheppard, for the murder of his wife, supporting in its decision that there was a "atmosphere of carnival in the trial" because of the media.
The crime is considered by some to have been the inspiration for the television and film "The fugitive."
Some lawyers have said that the Courts of Appeal for review half a century later the conviction of Mr. Hayes may be curious given the argument that new rules could be needed to manage the means of communication for the hearing rooms, unimaginable in the case of Dr Sheppard.
"there is a general right to worry about the impact of new media" in the trial, said John J. Donohue III, a professor at Stanford Law School who has studied the death penalty in Connecticut and wrote a report that it has been applied arbitrarily.
Professor Donohue says that some judges appeal could be intrigued by the idea that the limitation of instant communication from the courtrooms could allow fairer trial.
The case of Twitter is just one of many described by lawyers of Mr. Hayes, likely to be discussed for years, which will delay the execution.
Defence lawyers say, for example, that Mr. Hayes would have suffered damage when the judge Blue has refused to allow them to test the reactions of potential jurors by showing photos of macabre scenes criminal in the selection of the jury.
Some of the jurors said they had been horrified by the photographs of the victims, Jennifer Hawke-Petit, 48 years, and her daughters, Hayley, 17 years, and Michaela, 11 years.
Defence lawyers say they will also challenge the constitutionality of the death penalty and that they will argue that the judge has unjustly expelled one juror, who had been critical to prosecutors, and he has improperly put pressure for a verdict in taking the unusual decision to lead the jury to deliberate in a weekend.
The jurors were not sequestered.
But their arguments on the effect of the intense media coverage of the trial could be the largest source of interest.
They noted in a protest against the verdict, filed last month, that the case dominated media in Connecticut and that it was discussed during the election campaign by the candidates for governor and the Senate of the United States.
They have maintained that the media computer over fanning the flames of the emotion of the case.
"the scrambling daily tweets media, cameras and journalists to the palace of justice," the lawyers wrote, "looked nothing of what had been seen before in New Haven, and perhaps even at the national level."
Their emphasis on the cover of the system Twitter is controversial.
In interviews, some journalists have said that the claim that the new instant were more incendiary that releases recovered more slowly, was a sight luddiste that cutting the policy of the Court governing media coverage of future trials.
But some lawyers have said that the courts of appeal étaitent often attracted by the arguments that social change and technology required adaptation by the courts.
Lawyers for Mr. Hayes insist on this claim.
In their case, they are a reference to the Supreme Court's decision of 1966 who had overthrown the condemnation of Dr Sheppard because of media coverage of the trial and they made it clear that they invoqueraient need new rules for the new media.
"this affair," écrivaient-ils ," is that of Sheppard v. Maxwell's 21 th century."
Civility can bring the divisions?
After a campaign marked by invective and negativity, a minimum of civility in Washington this week.
Is this a harbinger of a genuine bipartisan cooperation forward or illusory moment before the rapid return to the partisan struggle in the capital?
The meeting Tuesday between President Obama and congressional leaders did not produce any breakthrough on the major issues that need to be addressed during the session of the "lame duck."
But obviously, there was at least a polite discussion on the differences between the two parties, as well as the recognition of their shared responsibility to govern, rather than another episode where each side wanted to score points. vacuum rating point supporter.
The public meeting Wednesday of the Committee on the president's deficit was equally civilized, despite the political differences between the members.
It seems clear that the close interaction of several months has created a mutual respect across the ideological divide; but which, however, still divides members.
It is barely enough to declare that a new era of cooperation has arrived.
The two parties are now in a trial period and tested mutual to obtain signs of cooperation and compromise, while trying to assess the limits of public opinion and the patience of voters for a partisan war.
That is why the meeting Tuesday and the subsequent comments from participants have unveiled a minimum requirements or accusations.
The philosophical differences between Obama and the Republicans are too big and too deep to suggest a rapid change of climate which has existed in the past two years.
Including taxation, spending, health care or human rights, the two sides remain at miles away.
However, the election of November had moderate Washington, at least in the short term.
"there is no doubt that things have changed the tone," said Pete Wehner, an official of the Bush administration, now at the side of the Centre for Ethics and Public Policy.
"it is inevitable after the elections.
The elections are causing partisan passions, and then they estomptent.
This is good. "
On some issues, particularly those on the agenda of "lame duck," Republicans and Democrats have no other choice than to find a solution.
Bush's tax cuts expire at the end of the year, and no one is in favour of it.
The two sides to find a way to preserve some or all, of a permanent or temporary.
Similarly, a compromise is possible on the extension of unemployment benefits, not least because the Republicans cannot afford to give the impression that they are in favour of tax cuts for the rich, while refusing the unemployment benefits to workers without jobs.
After the meeting Tuesday at the White House, more optimism about a possible agreement on the issues raised during the session on "lame duck," with the ratification of the pact "New START."
But William Galston of the Brookings Institution, warned that a fruitful cooperation on the most pressing problems of the session "blade" duck ménera does not necessarily lead to a better understanding between the two parties when the 112 th Congress convenes in January.
Instead, he says, a period of disagreement is likely, even inevitable.
"once things that need to be made the will, the psychology in the short term will return to a confrontation," he said.
Wehner also expressed its scepticism widely shared that civility would lead to a genuine cooperation.
"I think most of what happens between now and 2012 as a pré-spectacle or a shadow-boxing compared to the main event of 2012, at-il said.
The reasons are closely linked to the composition of the new Republican majority in the House and the voters at the tea that contributed to its creation.
However, Republican leaders are aware of the dangers if they go too far, they know they must try to live up to their promises to reduce public spending and to repeal the new law on health care.
These lines are already in the initial reactions to the recommendations of the Committee on the deficit which include reforming the tax code and to increase certain taxes, raise the retirement age and reduce spending.
The co-chairmen Alan Simpson and Erskine Bowles chose one of the most difficult tasks in Washington and have, by themselves, imposed the deficit on the public agenda in a way that cannot be ignored.
But they need 14 votes in the committee, composed of 18 members, to make their plan as an official recommendation, and they have struggled to reach this number.
The greatest resistance remains among the elected representatives of the group, which is on tax issues, at least today, little or willingness to compromise.
Galston provides two phases in the fighting between the White House and Republicans in Congress.
The first will come next year in the form of partisan battles, given that Republicans assail Obama on budget, tax and health care; and then be followed by a period of greater bipartisan cooperation.
What is the cause of change?
Public opinion.
It is demonstrated that, despite the partisanship of the recent election, a majority of Americans still wants to see the two parties to work together.
If the confrontation leads to a deadlock, as in 1995, when the two parties will be watching closely the public reaction.
Whoever is found in loss will change course and find compromises.
But this would be an optimistic view.
The partisanship and polarization are greater today than they did in the mid-1990 s and there seems to be more ideological gap between Obama and Republicans in Congress than there were then between President Bill Clinton and the Republicans.
At the same time, the activists of both parties see 2010 as a mere prelude to a larger election in 2012.
Given this reality, civility exposed this week could be appreciated by many Americans.
But it will take much more effort on the part of both parties to find common ground on the issues that still divide.
The American documents disclosed describe Moscow as a haven of corruption
Control of the city is in the hands of a "Kleptocratie" and until the Kremlin part of bribes and money for protection, reported the United States Embassy in Russia in a note in February.
The police and the Federal Security Service are making huge racketeering which helps to explain the high cost of living in Moscow, he said.
They collect money not only for legitimate businesses but also of organized criminal groups.
Each layer of bureaucracy - Prime Minister Vladimir Putin has called the "vertical of power" - takes their money in the pipeline to the top of the ladder.
The memo, which was sent to Washington as the Ambassador John Beyrle, was mailed Wednesday by WikiLeaks on its Web site.
The score is based on sources whose names have been cleared up.
It was written while Yuri Luzhkov was still mayor of Moscow; and he is largely responsible for corruption.
He was dismissed in October by President Dmitry Medvedev but there has been little evidence of cleaning.
Luzhkov and his wife, Elena Batourina, who owns a construction company, have always denied the accusations of corruption over the years; and he has won a libel case on these charges.
In September, he said that a Russian television station, when he was asked about a documentary suggesting he was corrupt: "It is crazy, it is to throw, this is nonsense."
The Russians believe, by an overwhelming majority, that their society is corrupt; according to the polls.
But it is unusual to find the information in a debriefing embassy; and it is incredible that this would be to diplomats from a foreign country to do so.
The direct link between the Moscow city government and crime has led some people in the name of "dysfunctional" and to say that the government functioned more as a kleptocracy that a government, "according to the notes of the embassy.
"the criminal elements have a" krysha " (a term used in the criminal world / mafia which literally means" roof "or protection) which passes through the police, the Federal Security Service (FSB), the Ministry of the Interior (MVD) and the prosecutor's office, as well as throughout the bureaucracy of the Moscow city government.
"analysts to identify a three-tier structure in the criminal world of Moscow."
"Luzhkov is at the top."
"the FSB and MVD, the militias are at the second level."
"finally, ordinary criminals and corrupt inspectors are at the lowest level."
"it is an inefficient system in which criminal groups fills a gap in some areas where the city does not provide some services."
The report indicates that the FSB is handling the money of the largest companies and that the police target small.
A source, he said, "explained that business owners of Moscow understood that it was better to get the protection of the FSB and MVD (rather than organized crime groups), not only because they have more weapons, more resources and more power than the criminal groups but they are also protected by the law."
"that is why the demand for protection by criminal gangs is not as high."
The memo noted that, although the collection of money is extended, the protection itself can be uneven; even those who pay are sometimes subject to arrest.
Those who do not pay quickly see their businesses close under one pretext or another.
Medvedev has repeatedly addressed the fight against corruption but he admitted the little progress.
The notes of the Embassy transmitted by reports of men who bring suitcases, probably commercial-operation money, until the Kremlin.
"in its fight against corruption, Medvedev depends bureaucrats," said in a recent interview Gueorgui Satarov, director of the "think tank" Indem of Moscow.
"but it is part of the bureaucracy."
"it is not part of a political class because they do not exist in Russia."
Without the policy, without opposition, without separation of powers, he said, corruption is inevitable.
According to the Indem, the costs of corruption would rise, the scale of Russia as a whole, to more than $300 billion per year.
The country was ranked 154 th in a recent survey on the overall perception of corruption by the non-governmental organization Transparency International (the countries are ranked at least more corrupt).
The disclosure of the notes of the American Embassy, which has been done yesterday, late in the evening, hour of Moscow, remuera with certainty of discontent within the Russian government; although Luzhkov can be blamed, to some extent for the failures of Moscow, this could be an opportunity for the Kremlin to show that it is in the process of solving the problem.
Interviewed by CNN's Larry King, Putin suggested that the documents to WikiLeaks could be a manufacturing and reacted with anger to the point that US diplomats had disclosed in the appellant Batman and Robin closer Medvedev.
"the problem is based on the fact that it is our interaction, an important factor in domestic politics in this country," he says.
"but to be honest with you, we thought that this would be done with such arrogance, such pressure and, you know, in opposition to the ethical."
Veterans of the Khmer Rouge forced to confront the past
In a classroom poorly lighted with walls of concrete warships, the director of secondary school to Anlong Veng spoke of the man who built, the last leader of the Khmer Rouge, Ta Mok.
"everyone here like Ta Mok."
"it was a good leader; and he cares about its people," said Sreng Kor Ma, 42 years old.
Known as "the butcher" for its brutality, when he was the head of the Khmer Rouge commander, remains popular in the isolated former Khmer Rouge stronghold in northwestern Cambodia where he has built hospitals, bridges and other infrastructure; and where thousands of former soldiers of the organization still live.
But this year, 12 years after the Khmer Rouge were in government, loyalty is finally called into question at Anlong Veng.
In April, a local forum of truth and reconciliation has allowed victims to confront publicly to people who had participated in the regime.
In June, the government has distributed a handbook of high school, for the first time, teaches the history of the Khmer Rouge to children of its soldiers.
And, in July, a Cambodian court, run jointly with the United Nations, made his first sentence for a former member of the Khmer Rouge, condemned to 35 years in prison, the former head of the notorious torture centre of Tuol Sleng, Kaing Khek Iev, better known as the "Duch."
In this evolution of the situation, the anxiety has increased among veterans of the Khmer Rouge to Anlong Veng; making reconciliation efforts and their wishes in Cambodian society.
"there is resentment and fear among the former Khmer Rouge but they are powerless to do anything," said Chhang Youk, director of the Documentation Centre of Cambodia, an independent organization that conducts research on the regime.
"for them, life under the Khmer Rouge was glorious but the regime has become a symbol of evil."
"the situation is creating divisions within families."
Under the Khmer Rouge in Cambodia, from 1975 to 1979, approximately 1.7 million people were executed or died of hunger, disease or overwork.
When the Vietnamese invaded and toppled the government of Pol Pot-Unis in 1979, the rest of the regime and its army have fled to the border of Cambodia and Thailand.
There, they have launched an insurgency that lasted until the last movements to visit in December 1998.
While Pol Pot, Nuon Chea and Ieng Sary ruled the guerrillas from their base located in the mountains of western Cambodia and in the jungle, Ta Mok was preparing a response to Anlong Veng.
But in the mid-1990 s, after a peace agreement sponsored by the United Nations has led to the first democratic elections in 1993, large groups of fighters Khmer Rouge began to make defection to the government, culminating with the capitulated to Ieng Sary in 1996 and Nuon Chea and Samphan in 1998.
Pol Pot died of natural causes in 1998 and Ta Mok, who had stood up, was captured by government forces in 1999 in the mountains near Dangrek.
He died in prison in Phnom Penh in 2006 pending his trial.
Without their benefactors, most veterans of the Khmer Rouge have sunk into poverty, common in rural areas of Cambodia; and many people are nostalgic for the movement.
Although some officers elite of the Khmer Rouge have retained their posts of local executives in exchange for putting down their weapons, it is farmers unskilled at low rank and file.
"these people have benefited from very little follow-up after the surrender," said Sok Leang Centre for justice and reconciliation which organizes public forums across Cambodia, including Anlong Veng.
"they are imbibés ideology utopian agrarian regime."
"they have been bred in a framework in which to do business is an alien concept."
SOR Lim, 55 -year-old, who joined the Khmer Rouge as a teenager in 1974, fought in the jungle around Anlong Veng before moving in 1998 as a producer of rice.
"life under the Khmer Rouge was good," he said.
"your Mok feeds everyone."
But now, life is difficult because we must meet our own needs. "
The Khmer Rouge Tribunal has also caused worries here.
The court should, at the beginning of next year, to start the trial of Nuon Chea Samphan, Ieng Sary and his wife, Ieng Thirith, another former Khmer Rouge.
The mandate of the court is prosecuting senior leaders and those most responsible for the crimes but has not said if he went beyond these four cases.
More may be needed to calm the fears of Anlong Veng.
The recent media speculation have turned to Im Chaem, aged 64, former head of district in the province of Banteay Meanchey under Khmer Rouge rule in the 1970 s.
In 2007, she told the researchers of the Documentation Centre of Cambodia that she had supervised the construction of Trapeang Thma, a project where thousands of workers forced to have died.
Recently, at a blistering Im Chaem Langdon's work in the field near her wooden house on pilotis, on a dirt road outside of Anlong Veng.
While the sun throwing long shadows on the grass scorched, Im Chaem refused to discuss his role in the Khmer Rouge.
If the court convened, she says, she refused to go there.
"Cambodia is peaceful and stable," said there.
"if there are more prosecutions, there will be war."
Prime Minister Hun Sen, who has done defection of Khmer Rouge in 1978, has also repeatedly warned that instability would happen if the court had sued several suspects, although experts and historians dispute this.
"Cambodia should dig a hole and bury the past, at-il said.
But confronting the past is what Cambodia needs to do to move forward, said Youk Chhang, the documentation centre.
"reconciliation in terms Khmer is to connect the pieces," he says.
"we need to put these pieces together so that we can understand."
The centre has produced the first manual approved by the government on the Khmer Rouge, "A History of the Democratic Kampuchea regime, consisting of 75 pages."
It was distributed to Anlong Veng in June as a supplement to the history books of the Ministry of Education, designed for high schools, which contained less than four pages on the Khmer Rouge.
As in most of Cambodia's young people Anlong Veng know only a few details on the Khmer Rouge, despite links to the city.
Valeak Touch, 19 -year-old student at the high school Anlong Veng, said that the new manual helping students understand a significant part of their history.
But his parents have reacted with skepticism when he returned with the book at home to study.
"my family rejects many parts of the manual and the court," he says.
"they are suspicious because they do not know exactly how many people the court will continue."
Such resistance has made the process of reconciliation complex and difficult, "said Sok Leang.
But the public forums, the manual and the court are beginning to have an impact, at-il said.
However, the Khmer Rouge retain a powerful atrait here.
Located in the mountains of Dangrek, a road, invaded by weeds and full of plastic bags, led to a rectangle of black soot, covered with a roof of corrugated rouillée.
The body of Pol Pot was burned here on a pile of tyres after his death in 1998.
Nuom Sothea, a 31 -year-old saleswoman mobile phone roadside said she did not know much about the man who was cremated at this location.
"but it has a great spirit; and many people go there to pray," she says.
