Belarus to give up its stockpile of uranium to weapons-grade
The government of Belarus announced Wednesday that it would abandon its stockpile of highly enriched uranium, a key component for nuclear weapons; this décison is part of a surprise victory in the campaign of President Obama to secure nuclear materials around the world
The agreement was disclosed in a joint communiqué issued after Secretary of State Hillary Rodham Clinton met by the Foreign Minister, Sergei Martynov, on the sidelines of a summit on security.
The US government had tried for years to convince Belarus to give up highly enriched uranium and seemed to have reached the horizon last spring.
But US officials have told the Washington Post that some trades were conducted with Belarus in the last two months to eliminate 187 pounds of uranium from a research centre of Belarus.
This has opened the way for an agreement Wednesday to eliminate the rest of the field of about 500 pounds, according to an official who spoke on the condition of anonymity because of the sensitivity of the issue.
The agreement appears to be one of the most important results of the Nuclear Security Summit of 47 nations, held at the initiative of Obama; when Belarus was excluded.
Apparently, it was good to obtain an invitation to the former Soviet republic following the summit, in 2012.
"I am really fascinated by the fact that they want a seat at the Nuclear Security Summit of 2012 nuclear security summit."
"it proves that this process works," said Ken Luongo, president of the Partnership for global security, a group of promotion of nuclear safety.
Clinton called the agreement "a very significant step," conducted by Belarus.
Obama has pledged to Prague in April 2009 to secure all vulnerable nuclear materials around the world in the next four years.
Since then, the US government has helped six countries to get rid of highly enriched uranium.
Belarus would be the seventh.
A dozen countries have done under the administration of George W. Bush.
At the time of the summit on nuclear security, Obama, the president of Belarus, Alexander Lukashenko, said that the nation would agree never to its uranium.
"we kept highly enriched uranium, hundreds of kilograms of what is essentially of uranium and uranium enriched," said Mr Lukashenko.
"it is our product... We are not going to make dirty bombs, and we will sell it to anyone."
"we will use it for research purposes, that is all."
Belarus has brought in line with the United States a few months ago; however, expressing interest in reaching an agreement.
The first implementation to eliminate uranium of Belarus, in October, has been particularly complicated because the material had been slightly irradiated, officials.
It was posted on a special train which has more than 1 300 miles to a facility in Russia to be stored and eliminated, officials.
The second operation was completed Monday and was conducted by plane, officials said.
The US government has spent $13 million in its efforts, in large part to replace the research facilities of Belarus with low-enriched uranium enriched; unsuitable for weapons.
"coordination and organization and have been implemented in order to strengthen confidence," leading to the agreement signed by Clinton, said Andrew Bieniawski, a Department of Energy specializes in reducing the Impending World.
According to estimates by the Center for the Study of Nonprolifération James Martin, Belarus had this year at least 88 pounds of uranium for weapons, as well as hundreds of kilograms of highly enriched uranium.
Belarus is seeking to eliminate its stockpile by 2012, according to a joint statement.
Relations between Belarus and the United States have been strained for years, mainly because of the harsh crackdown by Lukashenko of Human Rights.
But the statement Wednesday suggested a potential revival.
"while welcomimg progress on these issues of global security, the United States and Belarus have recognized that an increased respect for democracy and human rights in Belarus were essential to improve bilateral relations; and essential to the progress of the country and its citizens," she said.
