Red Bull triumph in F1 with a secret weapon of Siemens
Software creates improvements on cars in real time.
As soon as Red Bull tructurally entered the world of Formula 1 in 2004, its history in this sélecte universe of speed was marked by the surprise and success.
In a first time, no one has taken account of the options for a new stable who had just arrived, despite the upward trajectory of recent seasons, the last November, in the last phase of the championship all have bet on the triumph of Ferrari's Fernando Alonso.
Without discounting the skill as pilot's champion, the German Sebastien Vette, the capacity of the Renault engine that drives his car in the world of Formula 1 talks about the legend of the "secret weapon" that the multinational company Siemens has put in the hands of Red Bull to transform it into a winning team.
It is a powerful software simulation process that the company has launched on the market in 2007 with very distant goals of top-class automobilistique.
Appointed PLM, this powerful instrument technology has been used to create chains assembly factories fabricantes everyone stations, energy, high precision instruments.
The aim is to simulate faithfully reproduce the product or process before the building of a real, thus avoiding the flaws and avoidable costs.
Plm has facilitated the development of cameras to Canon, Sukhoi planes or more famous vehicles Nissan.
Siegfried Russwurm, head of the industrial division of Siemens, explains the fact that the use of this instrument computer in its plant in Formula 1 Red Bull to create and execute "in the coming hours, almost in real time," the changes, changes and improvements detected during races and trials.
Russwurm explains that the stables of 1992 had an average of 10 technicians in their teams who was able to introduce a maximum of three or four improvements on vehicles each season.
In the team of Red Bull work 180 young professionals of high qualifications which, equipped with powerful computer equipment and analyse plan any kind of changes on the speed-enthused.
The leader of Siemens explained that the software PLM is able to analyze and improve all elements of speed-enthused of Red Bull except the engine, which is the exclusive responsibility of Renault.
The materials, fuel, aerodynamics and security features.
The changes may pass from the virtual reality simulator to reality in less than 24 hours, thanks to advanced systems of production by laser and autoclaves high-tech.
As the only limitation of this madness of technological development there is the amount of $40 million that each team of Formula 1 can do limit each season to facilitate competition.
Red Bull has established the factory of high technology to create and produce its speed-enthused in a town 50 miles from London.
These are two buildings where the visits, especially for journalists, are restricted.
Everything that is happening there is considered "top secret."
Personnel for this duty has 580 people, ci-inclus two pilots, the champion Vettel and Mark Webber.
The hero of the Formula 1 Red Bull, without doubt, is the recent champion Sebastian Vetell.
Between the immense technological resources that the brand of energy drinks has the benefit of its participation in the circuits, there are other protagonists hidden, whose activity is priceless and visibility to zero.
The director of technology at the plant, Steve Nevey, says that five years ago you could say that the progress of R + D in the case of cars racing: 50% of victories and the pilots were responsible for the rest.
Today these percentages have changed and the technology represents a 85% success, while the pilots provide 15% of the value added.
Nevey admits that the Vettel or Webber will never be replaced by the computer, because "they are gladiators unpredictable."
