The leader of the Democratic majority in the Senate, Harry Reid, announced Tuesday that it would seek a "vote of closing the debate" in the Act tracks Act, which is why the initiative to legalize undocumented students could be passed from next Thursday in the Senate, even though most likely would be the next week.
The Senate version of the tracks Act or the Rêve American would legalise 800 thousand students who arrived in the United States before the age of 16 years, they have been in the past five years and they have been accepted by an institution of higher education or by the Army.
But supporters need 60 votes to approve the initiative, which is why they need the help of a large number of Republicans, in times when the partisan organizations project protagonists intense lobbying to secure the approval of the Act.
The Democrats, the majority which supports the tracks Act, have 58 seats.
But at least one of them, Senator Ben Nelson of Nebraska, said that he would vote against it and only a Republican has expressed support for the bill, Richard Lugar of Indiana.
That is why the supporters of the tracks Act require the vote of several Republicans if other Democrats decide to vote against the initiative.
Among Republicans courted ago Maine senators Olympia, Snowe and Susan Collins, and Senator outgoing George Lemieux, Florida, which has complemented the mandate process--the Senator Mel Martinez.
Other Republicans who have supported in the past the tracks Act are Orrin Hatch, of Utah, and Kay Bailey Hutchinson, of Texas, but they have said that they did not support another opportunity.
Another Republican who has supported, John McCain, has not defined its position so far.
Even if the House of Representatives has a different version, analysts agree with the fact that the greatest obstacles to the tracks are Act in the Senate.
