Dupont partially blamé
The radio of Quebec Stéphane Dupont has suffered a setback partial to the Canadian Council standards of broadcasting (non-CCNR) for controversial comments on social assistance and Haitians and vulgar language in waves.
The non-CCNR judge that Mr Meier and his team of CHOI 98.1 FM had the right to express their opinions, but that some of the comments contained "inaccurate information on social assistance, the unduly negative of Haitians and vulgar language which is not to be aired during the day."
The Council also concluded that a discussion on suicide, including the dissemination of the names of two people who have killed themselves, do not have violated the codes on broadcasting.
The non-CCNR had received several complaints about comments made during programs between 2008 and 2010.
The first decision was made following a complaint from the Common Front of social assistance recipients of Quebec.
The group complained that the amounts cited in the show were inaccurate.
The moderator must submit information solid rather than misleading.
On suicide, the facilitator Stéphane Dupont said that suicide is a gesture of cowardly.
The majority of the members of the Committee concluded that the message was that the suicide should not be seen as a solution to the problems of life.
"the majority of the Committee considers that the episodes involved" Dupont Concert "have touched a sensitive issue in a fair and appropriate."
No blame has therefore been adopted.
The last was statements after the earthquake in Haiti.
Stéphane Dupont and Jean-René Dufort were then delivered to a showdown media privately-retained reaction.
The facilitator of CHOI said he had no donation to help Haitians because we could not know with certainty that people would really need the money.
The Committee believes that these comments were not bad, but their cumulative effect is a representation of the Haitians unduly negative.
"I have already served my suspension of three days on this."
"my record is free for a year and a half," said the leader.
In all the decisions, the Committee denounces the dissemination of crude language.
In each case, the broadcaster CHOI-FM collaborated "beyond its obligation."
The consequences are minimal for the station which will, among other things, announce these decisions once during the prime-time within three days.
