"an inferiority complex Canadian almost inherent conditional perhaps political leaders to talk about domestic issues of daily life rather than to bring this election on the United States (as in the 1988 free trade)," he writes.
The United States are therefore, he concludes, "the proverbial elephant in this election: omnipresent, but potentially too threatening to talk about it."
The ambassador understands even less the "deafening silence" that the two countries have an intense political and economic relationship.
"logically, consider the ability of a candidate, party and even more of a party leader to manage this crucial relationship should be a key factor that voters have in mind by voting."
Another expression of this feeling of importance reads in the cable sent on 22 January 2009 by Terry Breese, Chargé d'Affaires in Ottawa, preparing President Barack Obama on his first visit to Ottawa.
"your trip will help ensure the survival of the government in the vote of confidence in early February on the federal budget, for which Canada will post its first deficit in more than a decade because of a stimulus package of $30 to $40 billion," wrote Mr Breese.
Nowhere is it mentioned that the government had to extend the Parliament before Christmas to avoid being overthrown by coalition and opposition parties blamed its survival conditional on the quality of the recovery plan proposed.
Another communication, dated January 2008 and signed by Ambassador Wilkins, warns Washington image increasingly negative as dramatic series broadcast on CBC pawn of the United States.
