A global plan to renovate lighting
The United Nations has proposed yesterday in Cancún a renovation plan lighting domestic, commercial and industrial clients in 100 countries in order to achieve a reduction of greenhouse gas (GHG) which represents a third of the additional reduction that remains to be done to stabilize the climate by 2020.
This ambitious plan will speak to large concrete projects that the United Nations hope to adopt in Cancun to compensate for the lack of binding commitments to reduce by industrialized nations.
According to the plan tabled yesterday, if the incandescent light bulbs, who monopolize again from 50 to 70% of the market were replaced by light bulbs fluorescents or, better, by lightbulbs light-emitting diodes (LEDs or "LED" in English), the bulk of the 1.8 billion tonnes (gigatonnes) GHG on the planet for humans would be avoided.
Lighting is responsible for 8% of global emissions.
This is equivalent to 70% of the car park.
In Copenhagen, the last year, the major emitters, such as the United States, China, Europe and others, including Canada, have been engaged in plans to reduce volunteers who should increase overall emissions of greenhouse gases to 53 gigatonnes to 49 gigatonnes.
But it will remove the record to 5 gigatonnes in order to stabilize by 2020, rising to 2 degrees centigrade in order to prevent it from becoming out of control.
In the incandescent light bulbs, 95% of energy is dissipated in the form of heat and the remaining 5%, a product of the light.
With light bulbs fluorescents, energy expenditure is reduced by 75% and with the new bulbs to LEDs, reducing the need for energy in two again.
The bulbs fluorescents last on average from 6000 to 10 000 hours.
The new bulbs to LEDs, such as those that launched the manufacturing Philips this week - the company has participated in the study of the United Nations - have a life expectancy of 25 000 hours and consume 80% less energy than a light bulb is heating up, which gives an idea of the economy with a possible replacement plan that would apply to 100 countries.
These new light bulbs can also work with rhéostats in addition to making very little heat.
And they provide no mercury.
Several experts have expressed reservations about the light bulbs fluorescents because they contain mercury and eliminate as hazardous waste, which is not always possible in developing countries, unless the establishment of guidelines.
But, says the report, the main source of mercury emissions on the planet is not the bulb fluocompacte, but rather the coal-fired power plants, which emit much mercury to produce electricity wasted in incandescent light bulbs.
For these plants emit 25 000 tons of mercury annually.
The report details the gains that each country through this international program.
For example, Indonesia would save one billion dollars per year in purchases of electricity and eight million tonnes of CO2, the equivalent of 3.5 power stations whose construction would cost 2.5 billion.
The Ivory Coast in the nervousness ahead of the announcement of election results
UN Secretary-General Ban Ki-moon has called for the publication "without delay" the results of the presidential election in Ivory Coast, after the expiry of the deadlines.
"the Secretary-General underlines the need for the independent electoral commission to complete its work and to announce third-quarter results without further delay," said a spokesman for the head of the United Nations. "
"it calls on all Ivorian parties and institutions to act responsibly and to refrain from any action until the announcement of preliminary results."
Despite pressure from some foreign governments, the electoral commission has missed the deadline of midnight Wednesday not to publish the results, three days after the vote on Sunday.
About forty minutes before the deadline, the chairman of the CIS said on television that the committee "continued to work" to announce the results.
Calls have multiplied Wednesday in the world for the CIS proclaims finally the name of the winner of the run-off between incumbent Laurent Gbagbo and the opposition leader Alassane Ouattara.
But the Gbagbo camp is counting on the annulment by the Constitutional Council votes "fraudulent" in the north, held by the ex-rebellion Forces (fn) since the failed coup of September 2002.
Pascal Affi N Guessan, campaign director of the Ivorian president, said that the intimidation of voters by the National Front in the north of the country had deterred the supporters of the outgoing president to vote.
Throughout the election could be reversed if the complaints by Gbagbo is kept by the Constitutional Council.
But opponents of Gbagbo believes that the highest court in the country is not neutral because it is headed by Paul Yao N Dré, a close political ally of Gbagbo.
Alassane Ouattara, the man North which denies any link with the former rebels, has "not acceptable" the delay in the announcement of the results and called on Gbagbo to respect them, but did not go so far as to claim victory.
His allies say that Gbagbo has blocked the publication of the results because he knows he has lost and file a complaint to the Constitutional Council, having prevented the electoral commission to disseminate the results, would be illegal.
The second round of the presidential election on Sunday, was supposed to complete the process of reunification and reconciliation to a country remained split into two for years.
The UN warned Wednesday the Ivorian political class that she could be held responsible for any violence.
Laurent Gbagbo had finished at the top of the first round, on 31 October, 38% to 32% - Alassane Ouattara, who has received public support of former president Henri Konan Bédié (25% in the first round).
The unemployment rate has remained stable in France in 3 th quarter
The unemployment rate in France in the sense of the International Labor Office (ILO) has remained stable at 9.3% in mainland France (9.7% including the overseas departments), show the data was adjusted for seasonal variations (CVS) interim published Thursday by the Insee.
The number of unemployed to 2.631 million in metropolis.
The second quarter were confirmed in 9.3% of the workforce in mainland France and 9.7% with the overseas departments.
About a year, the unemployment rate is rising by 0.1 percentage point.
More broadly, 3.4 million people in metropolitan France were not working in the third quarter but wanted to work, whether or not they are available in two weeks to work and that they are looking for a job.
The situation of young people on the labour market has deteriorated, with a further rise in the unemployment rate, 24.2% in mainland (+ 0.9 point in three months, + 0.5 points on a year) and 25% including the overseas departments.
In the third quarter, 637 000 of 15 to 24 -year-olds were unemployed in the sense of the ILO.
Older people have experienced a slight increase in unemployment, at 6.4% in mainland France (+ 0.2 point in three months and a year), or 482 000 people 50 years or more, and 6.6% with the overseas departments.
Only 25-49 years have benefited from a stability of unemployment in the third quarter, to 8.3% in mainland France (0.1 point in three months, + 0.1 points on a year) and 8.8% in France.
The Insee does more than monthly unemployment rate since 2006, after a controversial on its method of calculation.
Eurostat, the statistical agency of the European Union on the other hand, continues to do so and announced Tuesday a rate of 9.8% to France (DOM) included in October after 9.9% in September.
