Clotilde Reiss affair: the Élysée Palace has exaggerated the mediation of Syria
For more than ten months, from July 2009 to May 2010, the fate of the young French researcher Clotilde Reiss, arrested in Iran for "spying," held the opinion in suspense in France, put diplomacy, and further deterioration of relations between Paris and Tehran.
All under the watchful eye of US diplomats.
The American documents obtained by WikiLeaks and consulted by Le Monde reveal some below this crisis.
They describe how the Elysée Palace explained its strategy to Americans, up to give them advice for the treatment of their own crises "hostages" in Iran (a small group of hikers).
They show how French officials have sought to convince Washington that the release of young Frenchwoman had not been matched by the release of Majid Kakavand, an Iranian detained in France and the US for trafficking of materials for the benefit of Iran's nuclear program.
Finally, they place in a stark light on how the French Presidency has sought to manipulate the media to promote the idea that the Syrian president, Bashar al-Assad, had played a central role in the release of Clotilde Reiss.
In reality, there was nothing.
A diplomatic cable written on August 12, 2009 in Paris is entitled "Iran: French comments on how to deal with cases of hostages."
The Elysée adviser for strategic affairs, François Richier, accompanied by the director of the Quai d'Orsay in North Africa and the Middle East, Patrice Paoli, is holding discussions with the US diplomat Kathleen Allegrone.
They school-enrolment him the French method.
They advise the Americans to do the same to repatriate their own nationals retained power in Iran.
"made of noise," they say, "martelez constantly" in the media the words "fundamental human rights," "innocence," "immediate release."
He feels the need to embarrass the Iranian regime, sensitive to its image.
"do it all the more that the Iranians are asking you not to do so."
Because, past attempts to engage in discussions with discreet channels, "the silence will solve nothing," the Iranians are "masters in delaying tactics."
Mr Richier added that the arrest of foreigners is "a tactical Iranian familiar: the taking of hostages for political blackmail."
He said that the release from prison of Clotilde Reiss (Palouš on August 16, when she takes refuge at the French Embassy) "will require the payment to the Iranians to a large sum of money" (€230 000) bail.
And he said that the Elysée Palace anticipate other crises of hostages, a phenomenon which "will get worse."
The Iranians could "in the near future to stop another of some 1 800 French citizens living in Iran," he said.
28 August 2009.
Clotilde Reiss was released from prison for twelve days, but remains blocked in Iran.
Information is disseminated: the Iranian Majid Kakavand, including the US call for extradition for an illegal trafficking of sensitive electronic equipment to Iran, is released in Paris by decision of a judge.
The US Embassy, as many observers, is mulling over this troubling coincidence.
For Washington, which finds the clandestine networks Iranian acquisition of nuclear program, the enlargement of Majid Khakavand is bad news.
France accepted a bargaining?
The release of the Iranian against that of the French?
In a new interview with Kathleen Allegrone, on 4 September, François Richier ensures that this is not the case.
The Elysée Palace, he says, has not only been "completely taken by surprise by the judge's decision," but has sought to oppose it.
"there have been heated exchanges between the French Presidency and the Attorney-General" (at the time, Michèle Alliot-Marie), but "the French government cannot return to the judicial decision," drift.
Mr Richier also wants to demonstrate that Majid Kakavand remains under the "closely monitoring" the French intelligence services.
The adviser to the Elysée Palace a telephone number, clutching, then informs the American diplomat that Iran "is currently located in buildings in Paris managed by the Iranian Embassy."
During the detention of Clotilde Reiss in Iran, the Elysée Palace is sparing no efforts, through communiqués and "leaks" in the media, to make us think that Syrian President Bashar al-Assad plays a role "influential" of "mediator."
The Americans are watching this activity without irony, and find that the manipulation is bearing fruit as several press articles reflected the official French version.
A telegram dated August 25, 2009 evokes "a media blitz, the official French."
What is at the heart of both "" expressed gratitude to Mr Assad, wonders Embassy in Paris.
"despite their statements of praise, French officials privately admit that they have only a vague notion of what the Syrians have really done."
The document then considers the reasons that led to the Elysée Palace into this fiction.
The intense effort of communication "aims to validate Sarkozy's policy of opening to Syria," that analyses.
A policy launched in 2008, "which was seen by many critics in France and abroad, as premature and undeservedly."
In "exaggerating the role of Syria," Paris "seeks to demonstrate to Syria praised what she can draw by playing a constructive role in the region."
The aim is also to "sow the seeds of discord between Syria and Iran."
The US Embassy knows a good source.
On August 11, François Richier entrusted to him: "Of course, we do not know if the Syrians have done anything."
"but we get."
"this should at least cause confusion among Iranians."
Clotilde Reiss falls in France on 16 May 2010.
Nicolas Sarkozy received at the Elysée Palace.
In a statement, he thanked the presidents of Brazil, Senegal, and Syria, for their "active role for the release of our compatriot."
No online games for young Koreans past midnight
The South Korean government will adopt a law so-called "Cinderella" which prohibit teenagers to play games online after midnight by blocking their access, government officials.
A bill will be submitted to Parliament in December to ask companies to online games to block access to these games after midnight, young people under the age of 16, representatives from the ministries of culture and family.
"a lot of children were playing these games all night and then have difficulty at school and to have a normal life during the day."
"we believe that this law is needed to ensure their health and their right to sleep," said to AFP Jo Rin, the ministerial in charge of the bill.
Online games will be accessible to 6 hours of the morning.
Companies will have a year to prepare for the application of the law, he said.
The government also plans to ask companies to limit the time daily access to these games for young people whose parents request it, "said responsible.
It will also be available to people who call for free software to limit the time spent on the Internet.
South Korea is one of the most "connected" and newspapers T4008 regularly news related to intensive use of the Internet.
The country is also the undisputed champion world competition from online games.
In November, South Korea had won four gold medals at the World Cyber movie, faced with 58 other nations.
