Euro: ECB forced to maintain its purchases of government securities
The last meeting of the Governing Council of the European Central Bank (ECB) of the year should be the opportunity of clarifying the exit, or at least to announce the arrest of a number of operations unconventional monetary policy which must be achèver at the end of the year.
Sovereign debt crisis, the European Institute of Frankfurt will probably not be able to afford to be as compelling as only worsen the situation more tense today on European bond markets.
The political cost would be even higher.
Yesterday, at a press conference, the French finance minister, Christine Lagarde, has welcomed the active role played by the ECB in favour of the resolution of the debt crisis of states in Europe.
She did not want to say whether they believed that the central bank should do more, such as increasing its program to buy sovereign bonds.
"I reserve my reflection in my European partners (...) ."
The day before, in Brussels, during his hearing with the Committee on Economic and Monetary Affairs of the European Parliament, the President of the ECB, Jean-Claude Trichet, has not been more said about his intentions, and indicate that the program to purchase government securities on the secondary market "continues," and that "we will see what we decide," at the meeting this Thursday.
One certainty: the ECB will keep its main interest rate unchanged at 1%, the lowest level on record since May 2009.
In fact, purchases of Treasuries by the ECB have doubled in the last week, to nearly 1.35 billion euros.
And, according to the indiscretions of market operators, it would have new purchases of securities Irish and Portuguese, yesterday.
In total, the central banks of the Eurosystem have bought for 67 billion euros since May 2010.
Operators of market expectations of a further purchases are (see page 29).
Economists did not expect any major change of direction.
If the loan operations in more than three months have already disappeared in the arsenal of the ECB, the latter again to careprovider unlimited liquidity under conditions and generous to last from one week to three months.
Economists now expect that to be extended for a few months.
"I can't imagine that it changes significantly its program."
"otherwise it would risk further tensions in the short term," said Michael Schubert, economist of the Commerzbank.
"a gradual phasing-out announced during the first quarter of 2011 seems more likely," is his side Norbert Bräms, economist at Sal.
Oppenheim.
In terms of its interventions in the market of public debt, "the ECB should maintain a volume of buying bonds to tackle a sluggish market," says Norbert Bräms.
Given the importance of the exposure of European banks to the markets of sovereign debt in the euro zone, the institute emission has no choice but to maintain its presence on the market.
"he should replace the lack of investors on the market and act to prevent a soaring yields paid by even the most fragile," has an important bond manager yesterday.
Because if interest rates are soaring, the states would be embarrassed to reduce their debt, if not the stabilizing.
The euro is the price.
In Italy, the Berlusconi government to the back round-wood
After the beginning of the week worrying for Italy, the situation is a little relaxed, yesterday, with the decline in bond rates in 10 years.
A precarious calm.
In a meeting with the Minister of the Economy, the presidents of the region have said he has heard Giulio Tremonti describe the situation of "indecipherable" and expect a weekend "unpredictable," that the person was then denied.
Tuesday, in any case, the gap with the long rates German had reached the record of 210 basis points and the price of contracts to hedge against the risk of bankruptcy (CDS) had soared to 263 points, resulting in a certain panic in Rome.
The Council of Ministers, Silvio Berlusconi has pointed out that in Spain, the gap with the German rate was above 400 basis points.
But his right arm, Gianni Letta, said he was "deeply concerned" by "the turbulence in the markets" and a possible contagion from Ireland.
"the good news is that Italy, third economy of the euro area, is not as Greece or Ireland."
"the bad news is that it is like Portugal," says Irwin Stelzer, economist at the Hudson Institute.
Clearly, the problem is the lack of growth and tax revenues that goes with that, with the state may not be able to cover its financing needs.
The latest forecasts by Brussels were a cold shower for the government.
The Italian growth is now expected to 1.1% in 2011 and 1.4% in 2012... so that the budget being considered in the Senate on 1.3% and 2% respectively.
In these conditions, the European Commission, the public deficit will represent 4.3% of GDP next year (against 3.9% planned by the government) and 3.5% in 2012 (instead of 2.7%).
Where the rumor of a new collective budget that could be put in place after the holidays, for an amount of EUR 7 billion.
"if necessary, new austerity measures will be taken," according to the Economic Affairs Commissioner, Olli Rehn.
For the moment, Italy has the support of international institutions.
"the fundamentals of the economy are in order and its accounts are good, we have been saying for a long time," assures Arrigo Sadun, the Italian director at the International Monetary Fund in charge of Italy to the IMF.
"there is no problem in the immediate, short-term or long-term, for despite its debt (119.2% of GDP in 2011, stitch), stabilization requested to Italy are lower than those required of other countries," observes Pier Carlo Padoan, chief economist of the OECD.
There remains the question of political instability.
On 14 December, Silvio Berlusconi faces up to a vote of no confidence in the Chamber of Deputies, early elections could be held in late March.
It would open a period that is not conducive to decision-making in the event of a serious crisis.
