"as in May, there is a real lack of clarity and visibility policy, in particular the banking systems," say economists to Exane BNP Paribas.
All the more that "time is slower than the time markets."
Aware of this and of the dangers, European countries are stepping up discussions to strengthen the anti-crisis devices already existing.
The informal consultations between the Finance Ministers most directly concerned and, more broadly, with their peers from the G20.
And also in view of the Eurogroup and the Ecofin meetings from early next week.
The ECB meets today.
On the menu, the fate of unconventional measures to support the countries of the euro zone in the bull markets (see above).
On the European Financial Stability Fund (EFSF), its executive director, Klaus Regling, began Tuesday in Singapore to Asia for investors extrême-orientaux developments of the crisis in Europe.
