Hackers revenge and spies in
Dehauller WikiLeaks has a dual value.
On the one hand, it is a manifest scandal, a scandal which appears as scandal that before the hypocrisy which governs relations between states, citizens and the press.
On the other, it promises profound changes at the international level, and suggests a future dominated by the regression.
But in order.
The first aspect of WikiLeaks, this is confirmation of the fact that each record by a secret service (of any nation) is composed exclusively of press clippings.
The "extraordinary" American revelations about the sexual habits of Berlusconi are repeating what for months could be read in any newspaper (except those which Berlusconi owns), and the profile eerily caricature of Gaddafi was for cabaret artists, to SKIT.
The rule that the secret files should be compounds that new already known is essential to the dynamics of the secret services, and not only in this century.
If you go into a bookshop dedicated to publications esoteric, you will see that each book repeat (on the Holy Grail, the mystery of Rennes-le-Château, Templiers or Rose-Croix) exactly what was written in the past.
And not only because the author of texts occult don't like to research new (or knows where to look for new on the non-existent), but because those dedicated to occultism only believe in what they already know, and confirm that they had already learned.
It is the mechanism of the success of Dan Brown.
For secret files.
The informant is lazy, lazy and (or) spirit limited the head of the secret services (otherwise it could be, whatever, editor of Libération), which is as true that what he acknowledges.
The top secret information on Berlusconi that the US embassy in Rome sent the State Department were the same as those that Newsweek published the week before.
So why the revelations about these issues they have made so much noise?
On the one hand, they say that any cultured person, namely that the embassies, at least since the end of the Second World War, and since the heads of states can call or a plane to meet for dinner, have lost their diplomatic service and, except for a few years of representation, into centres of espionage.
Any viewer of films serious-crimes knows this very well, and it is only by hypocrisy that we pretend to ignore.
However, the fact of the repeat publicly violates the duty of hypocrisy, and serves to put in a bad light.
Second, the idea that a hacker would capture the secrets more secrets of the world's most powerful country is a significant blow to the prestige of the State Department.
As the scandal not aggravating both in crisis victims that the "perpetrators."
But the very nature of what happened.
Once, at the time of Orwell, one could imagine any power as a Big Brother who controlled every gesture of his subjects.
The prophecy Orwellian was completely proven since, that can monitor every movement through the telephone, each transaction, the hotel, visited the motorway taken and so on, the citizen became the victim of the eye of the total power.
But when it is demonstrated, as it happens now, even the cryptes secrets of power cannot escape the control of a hacker, the monitoring report ceases to be unidirectional and becomes circular.
The power control every citizen, but every citizen, or at least the hacker - elected as avenger of the citizen - can know all the secrets of power.
How a power that was no longer able to keep its own secret can take?
It is true, Georg Simmel said already, that a true secret is a secret (secret vacuum and vacuum will never be revealed); it is true, also, that know everything about the character of Berlusconi or Merkel is actually a secret vacuum of secrecy, because in the public domain; but reveal, as did WikiLeaks, that the secret of Hillary Clinton were secret empty means putting any power.
WikiLeaks has done no harm to Sarkozy or to Merkel, but has done too much to Clinton and Obama.
The consequences of this wound inflicted on a power very powerful?
It is clear that in the future, states can no longer put online no information reserved - that would be to publish on a poster hung up on the street corner.
But it is equally obvious that with current technology, it is vain hope to maintain the confidential reports by telephone.
Well, it's easy to find out if and when a head of state has shifted in aircraft and approached one of his colleagues.
How can be maintained in the future rules--that private and reserved?
I am well aware that, for now, my prediction is science fiction and is therefore romantic, but I am obliged to imagine government officials who move so quiet in the procedures for routes uncontrollable, being carriers that messages learned by heart or, at most, by hiding the rare written information in the Achilles a shoe.
The information will be stored in a single copy of drawers closed to key: basically, the attempted espionage of Watergate has had less success that WikiLeaks.
I had the opportunity to write that the technology is now in crab, i.e. backwards.
A century after the telegraph wireless revolutionized communications, the Internet has restored a telegraph on son (telephone).
The video (analogue) had allowed the researchers to explore a cinema film step by step, by going forward and back and see all the secrets of the assembly, while now CDs (digital) do that to jump to chapter by chapter, i.e. by macroportions.
With high-speed trains, it goes from Rome to Milan in three hours, while in flight, andparticipants includes it takes three and a half hours.
It is therefore not extraordinary that the political and technical communications in the cars on horseback.
A final observation.
Previously, the press was trying to understand what was going on in secret embassies.
Now, they are the ones who demand the confidential information to the press.
Climate: how France quick fix its promises of funding
A year after the advent of Copenhagen, it is time to examine the promises of funding quickly released (so-called fast start funding or early) made by developed countries.
And the big cobble French are revealed.
In the Copenhagen agreement, developed countries are committed to providing $30 billion between 2010 and 2012.
The European Union has pledged 7.2 billion euros over three years and France 1.26 billion euros ($420 million per year).
At the opening of the COP16, the EU has lifted the great game to persuade its partners to the reality of his commitment to the fast start funding: report detailing the activities of its member states, press conference, great side event, distribution of brochures...
The transaction transparency is welcome and appreciated: developing countries and civil society would like all developed countries to do the same with the same level of precision.
The EU have reached 2010 2.2 billion euros, which puts it on the right path for the commitment of $7.2 billion in 2012.
But when you look in detail, things are more complicated.
This money must be, according to the Copenhagen agreement, "new and additional," to ensure that extra effort is made without being at the expense of official development assistance.
Unfortunately, there is no agreement on what it means to "new and additional."
While the European Commission had proposed harmonization, some member states including France have blocked the procedure.
Today, everyone chooses the reference that best suits them.
The European Commission has, for example, regarded as the reference year 2009: the international funding, and $150 million over three years funding fast start.
Other countries have chosen references similar in terms of the year or in terms of the level of official development assistance.
By contrast, France believes that the "all new projects" of 2010 are "new and additional."
In other words, there is no reference to the spending of the previous years or the overall level of official development assistance.
Specifically, the total amount of support from France to developing countries can remain stable (or even less), it claims its commitment to funding "new and additional..."
Another crucial element, the division between donations and loans.
Again, there is no rule and everyone chooses its calculation.
Some, like France, consider that lent €1 amounts to €1 given.
Of course, it is hard to justify: the effort is not comparable.
If the use of loans can be justified for certain investments profitable (often projects related to the reduction of emissions which are based on more efficient technologies), it is misleading to present an euro that will be recouped as equivalent to an euro that is given... the more, should be counted as part of its commitments that the cost of the loan to the lender countries (the equivalent of an interest rate).
But France has a line of reasoning: it "respects" its commitment of EUR 420 million with 91.5% of loans (389.8 million) and 8.5% of donations (36.1 million euros) - the EU to check for yourself.
It is the only country of the European Union to use such a loan.
Germany by 46%, while Denmark, the Netherlands and Slovakia (other) respect their commitments with 100% of donations.
In other words, when the vast majority of the European Union puts 1 to meet its commitment, France is only 10 cents and considers that the effort is comparable.
Good trick!
In summary, in his fast start funding, France operates a double scam: on the one hand on the evolution of the action in the time and the reality of the financial effort.
While spending 36.1 million euros, it suggests that it spends 420 million "new and additional" consistent with its promises.
The manipulation of the Department of Finance (because it appears that the Bercy who has done the arbitration) could have a double negative impact, both within the EU (why the other member states would continue to give it just?) and in the negotiations since developing countries are not completely fooled...
The chapter of funding early is a small issue, on the short term, in the context of discussions on the climate.
But it could be a grain of sand in the huge machine that is the UNFCCC.
Let us hope that this is not the case.
However, it is necessary to learn the lessons of this first year of funding early.
First, France could announce a change in the way of accounting for the years 2011 and 2012, in a spirit of respect its commitments and equity with the other countries of the European Union.
But above all, France could push the discussions on the issues of long-term finance (another crucial chapter discussed today: we will not escape the question of "additionality" or the method of calculating loans.
France could change his position to become too progressive on these issues than on others.
The hope is the new Minister of the Environment, Mrs Kosciusko-Morizet, which will arrive in Cancun next week.
A surprise announcement on the fast start of France and its vision of "additionality" and the use of loans would increase the level of international confidence necessary for progress in the discussions.
Alert to pesticides ingested by children
A 10 -year-old child consumed in a day, 81 different chemicals, according to a study published Wednesday in the association Générations Futures (ex- Movement for Rights and respect of future generations).
The association, which warns that its results "have no value statistically significant in view of the low number of samples analyzed, but are to include the issue addressed," has purchased between July and September foods generally consumed in four meals and a snack in one day by a child of a decade, in the supermarkets in the Oise and Paris.
These meals types, including formal recommendations - five fresh fruit and vegetables, dairy products and three 1.5 litre of water per day - as well as sweets, were examined by laboratories in search of chemicals, pesticides, heavy metals and other pollutants.
The balance sheet of the base is damning: 81 chemicals, 42 of which are classified as carcinogenic possible or probable and five substances classified as carcinogens and some 37 substances that act as endocrine disruptors (EP), according to studies by several institutions like the International Agency for Research on Cancer.
"even if, in almost all cases, the legal limits for each chemical substance taken individually are not exceeded, it is clear from our investigation that the reality of consumer exposure to contaminants possibly carcinogenic and / or EP is worrying," notes the association.
For breakfast, butter and milk tea contain for more than a dozen carcinogenic residues possible and three proven as carcinogenic and some twenty residue that can disrupt the hormonal system.
The potato, imported from Brazil, planned as a snack for the study, presented traces of six chemicals with a fungicide but banned in France.
Same thing for the green beans from Kenya, included in the lunch, on which the study has detected traces of a powerful insecticide banned in the EU.
Moreover, the minced meat, canned tuna, and even the wand of bread and the chewing gum were full of pesticides and other chemicals.
In the analyses revealed the presence of nitrates and chloroform.
For dinner, the steak of salmon was the most "rich" with 34 chemical residues detected and even the examination of the plate plastic used to warm the meals micro-onde was not free.
The final risk to the consumer of the "cocktail" of contaminants "is probably underestimated," according to the study.
The Alliance Europe Ecologie-Les Greens (EE-LV), for its part, has proposed "faced with the urgency of the situation" to establish a moratorium on the use of pesticides, in order to "stop the increase in diseases of civilisation."
In July, a study of the European Food Safety Authority (EFSA) was the presence of residues of 365 different pesticides identified in fruit and vegetables consumed in Europe, 76 in the grain.
